This site is built with Rails. Posts are saved as static files but accessed through Active Record. It is deployed on heroku for free.

There is a (non-publicly accessible) page on this site to create a new post. It is essentially a WYSIWYG editor because it allows writing HTML code which is drawn by the browser when the post is later viewed.

I can play with CSS, too, like below:

<style> 
.animated { 
    -webkit-animation-duration: 3s; 
    animation-duration: 3s; 
    -webkit-animation-fill-mode: both; 
    animation-fill-mode: both; 
    -webkit-animation-timing-function: linear; 
    animation-timing-function: linear; 
    animation-iteration-count:infinite; 
    -webkit-animation-iteration-count:infinite; 
} 

@-webkit-keyframes pulse { 
    0% { -webkit-transform: scale(2); } 
    50% { -webkit-transform: scale(1.1); } 
    100% { -webkit-transform: scale(2); } 
} 
@keyframes pulse { 
    0% { transform: scale(2); } 
    50% { transform: scale(1.1); } 
    100% { transform: scale(2); } 
} 
.pulse { 
    -webkit-animation-name: pulse; 
    animation-name: pulse; 
}
.pulseball {
 background: black;
 width: 40px;
  box-shadow: 0px 0px 50px red;
  height: 40px;
  border: 1px solid black;
  border-radius: 40px;
}

</style>

<div class="pulseball animated pulse"></div>

<br><br><br><br>

That was done by a CSS animations generator, by the way ... I'm still learning how to make them.
This is the code: <br> <xmp>
<style> 
.animated { 
    -webkit-animation-duration: 3s; 
    animation-duration: 3s; 
    -webkit-animation-fill-mode: both; 
    animation-fill-mode: both; 
    -webkit-animation-timing-function: linear; 
    animation-timing-function: linear; 
    animation-iteration-count:infinite; 
    -webkit-animation-iteration-count:infinite; 
} 

@-webkit-keyframes pulse { 
    0% { -webkit-transform: scale(2); } 
    50% { -webkit-transform: scale(1.1); } 
    100% { -webkit-transform: scale(2); } 
} 
@keyframes pulse { 
    0% { transform: scale(2); } 
    50% { transform: scale(1.1); } 
    100% { transform: scale(2); } 
} 
.pulse { 
    -webkit-animation-name: pulse; 
    animation-name: pulse; 
}
.pulseball {
 background: black;
 width: 40px;
  box-shadow: 0px 0px 50px red;
  height: 40px;
  border: 1px solid black;
  border-radius: 40px;
}

</style>

<div class="pulseball animated pulse"></div>

</xmp>

(I'm also using the deprecated "xmp" tag to print that code without escaping the characters)
until I find a better way.